Name: Soarin' Around the World
Location: World Nature at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′21.66″N 81°33′9.43″W
Opening date: May 5, 2005
Height restriction: 40 inches
Duration: 4:51 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Small Drops
Overview/History:
Feel the thrill as you’re raised high in the air and swept from one scenic locale to the next. See the world’s wonders—natural and manmade—like you never have before. No mountain is too high. No landscape is too far.
Your journey begins as the clouds part above the majestic Swiss Alps. Next, you’ll visit polar bears in icy Greenland, swoop past sailboats on Australia’s iconic Sydney Harbour and weave between elephants marching toward Mount Kilimanjaro.
Glide above marvels like the Great Wall of China, the Great Pyramids of Egypt and the Taj Mahal in India. Cruise over Monument Valley, Fiji’s Lau Island and thundering Iguazu Falls in South America. Look down on the Eiffel Tower as it sparkles like a jewel in the night, surrounded by the lights of Paris.
The 180-degree, 80-foot IMAX digital projection dome, spectacular aerial footage, pleasant scents and graceful motion raise the soothing sensation of flight to incredible new heights.
Throughout your flight, you’ll be treated to the uplifting musical score, adapted by composer Bruce Broughton from the attraction’s unforgettable original score written by Academy Award-winner Jerry Goldsmith.
Soarin' was first conceptualized in 1996 as Ultra Flight, a name that can still be seen on the tower consoles of the California Adventure attraction. It was to feature an OMNIMAX screen with an inverted track, allowing guests to fly over California's landmarks. It was to have three load levels, with a system operating on a horizontal cable, much like a dry cleaner's rack. The plan was abandoned when it was determined that the design's construction and labor costs would be prohibitive. It seemed that Soarin' wouldn't become a reality until engineer Mark Sumner developed a different idea for the ride vehicles, using an Erector Set and string to create a working model. The new design allowed Disney to efficiently load guests on one level instead of three, significantly cutting its building costs.
Each ride vehicle consists of three rows of seats under a wing-like canopy, with a capacity of 87 guests. After guests have been safely restrained in the vehicle with standard lap belts, the canopy descends slightly and a cantilever system lifts the chairs forward and into the air with the guests' feet dangling freely. The vehicle is lifted forward so that guests look into a large, concave movie screen onto which aerial views are projected. The original film's scenes were shot at an IMAX HD frame rate of 48 frames per second, twice the conventional rate of regular films. The vehicle is moved forward toward the center of the dome so guests can see only the projected images and experience the sensation of flight. The ride structure contains about one million pounds (454,000 kg) of steel; 37 tons (33.5 metric tonnes) are lifted during each ride cycle.
To enhance the illusion, subtle vertical movements of the seats are synchronized to the film. Sensations of horizontal motion are created with a combination of vertical carriage movement and turning the image on the screen. Scents complementing the scenes are also injected into the air streams blowing on riders. When it opened, the scent was only present during the Redwood Creek scene and the Valencia Orange Farms scene. In the updated show, scents include rose blossoms in the Taj Mahal scene, grass in the Africa scene, and a sea breeze in the South Pacific scene.

Name: Spaceship Earth
Location: World Celebration at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′31″N 81°32′58″W
Opening date: October 1, 1982
Height restriction: None
Duration: 15:00 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
Spaceship Earth is an iconic dark ride attraction housed within the geodesic sphere that serves as the symbolic structure of EPCOT. This slow-moving omnimover attraction takes guests on a time machine-themed journey through the history of human communication, from the dawn of time to the digital age and beyond.
As you ascend through the massive sphere, you'll witness key moments in communication history brought to life through impressive audio-animatronics and immersive sets. The journey begins with early humans developing language and creating cave paintings. You'll then travel through ancient civilizations, witnessing the development of hieroglyphics in Egypt and the invention of the alphabet by the Phoenicians.
The ride continues through pivotal moments such as the Renaissance, where you'll see Michelangelo painting the Sistine Chapel, and the invention of the printing press by Johannes Gutenberg. As you progress, you'll experience the Industrial Revolution, the invention of the telephone, and the dawn of the computer age.
Near the top of the sphere, your time machine will rotate backwards, treating you to a breathtaking view of Earth from space. As you descend, you'll get a glimpse into potential future communication technologies before concluding your journey.
Spaceship Earth has undergone several updates since its 1982 opening. The attraction has featured different narrators over the years, including Lawrence Dobkin (1982-1986), Walter Cronkite (1986-1994), Jeremy Irons (1994-2007), and currently Dame Judi Dench (2007-present). Each update has brought new scenes, improved technologies, and refreshed narratives while maintaining the core theme of human communication.
The geodesic sphere itself is an engineering marvel. It stands 180 feet tall, with a diameter of 165 feet. The sphere is covered by 11,324 alucobond tiles, creating its distinctive appearance. The entire structure weighs an impressive 15,520,000 pounds.
The ride system uses Omnimover vehicles that can hold 4 riders each, arranged in two rows of two. The track spirals up and down within the sphere, allowing for a smooth and continuous loading process. To enhance the experience, the musical score for each scene features styles and instruments appropriate to the time period depicted.
At the conclusion of the ride, guests exit into Project Tomorrow, an interactive play area that showcases potential future technologies. This post-show area has evolved over the years, previously known as Earth Station and later as the Global Neighborhood.
Spaceship Earth remains one of EPCOT's most popular and iconic attractions, combining education and entertainment in classic Disney style. It continues to inspire guests with its grand vision of human progress and the potential of future communication technologies.

Name: Test Track
Location: World Discovery at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′24″N 81°32′52″W
Opening date: March 17, 1999 (original version), December 6, 2012 (current version)
Height restriction: 40 inches (102 cm)
Duration: About 5 minutes
Thrill level: High-speed, Thrill Rides
Overview/History:
Test Track is a high-speed slot car thrill ride that simulates the c concept cars and video screens where engineers discuss car design. In the Chevrolet Design Center, guests use large touchscreen interfaces to create their own concept car, choosing the body, engine, wheels, trim, and color. Each design decision impacts the car's capability, efficiency, responsiveness, and power.
After designing their vehicle, guests board a six-passenger "SIM Car" for a thrilling ride through the testing facility. The ride consists of four different tests: capability, efficiency, responsiveness, and power.rigorous testing procedures used by General Motors to evaluate its concept cars. The attraction takes guests through the process of designing their own vehicle and then "testing" it in a high-speed drive through and around the pavilion.
As guests enter the pavilion, they pass displays of sleek, futuristi These tests include braking maneuvers, cornering, and acceleration. The highlight of the attraction is the final power test - a high-speed drive around the exterior of the building, reaching a top speed of 64.9 miles per hour (104.4 km/h), making it the fastest attraction at Walt Disney World.
Test Track has a rich history at EPCOT. It replaced the World of Motion attraction, which closed in 1996. The original version of Test Track opened in 1999 after significant delays and a cost of approximately \$300 million, making it one of the most expensive theme park attractions in the world. The ride underwent a major refurbishment in 2012, shifting from a physical testing facility to a digital design environment, though the ride experience with the high-speed finale remained largely unchanged.
The attraction features state-of-the-art technology, including the ride system itself. Each vehicle is a slot car, drawing power from the track while being free to move within its slot, allowing for precise control of vehicle speeds and the ability to slow or stop vehicles wherever necessary. This system ensures both thrilling experiences and a high degree of safety.
After the ride, guests can use their MagicBand, ticket, or design key to see their scores from the ride, play games, and create ads in the "Chevrolet Showroom." They can also check out some of the newest Chevrolet vehicles and take virtual photos with their custom-designed cars.
Test Track is consistently one of the most popular attractions at EPCOT, often featuring long wait times. To manage this, Disney offers both a Lightning Lane option through Disney Genie+ and a single-rider line, which can significantly reduce wait times for those willing to split up their party.
The attraction's popularity and technological advancements have inspired similar rides in other Disney parks, such as Radiator Springs Racers at Disney California Adventure, which uses a similar ride system themed to the "Cars" franchise.

Name: Journey into Imagination with Figment
Location: World Celebration at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′24″N 81°32′52″W
Opening date: June 2, 2002 (current version)
Height restriction: None
Duration: 7 minutes and 30 seconds
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
Journey into Imagination with Figment is a whimsical dark ride that takes guests on a tour of the Imagination Institute, led by Dr. Nigel Channing and the mischievous purple dragon, Figment. This attraction is the third iteration of the Journey into Imagination concept, which has been a part of EPCOT since the park's opening in 1983.
As you board your "tour tram," Dr. Channing (played by Eric Idle) introduces you to the Imagination Institute's sensory labs. However, Figment (voiced by Dave Goelz) quickly appears and playfully disrupts each of the five sensory experiments: Sound, Sight, Smell, Touch, and Taste. Throughout the ride, Figment encourages guests to use their imagination and think "outside the box," often to Dr. Channing's frustration.
The journey begins in the Sound Lab, where Figment interrupts the experiment with silly noises. In the Sight Lab, he alters an eye chart and starts a "One Little Spark" sing-along. The Smell Lab features Figment as a skunk, releasing a humorous (but actually pleasant) scent. In the Touch and Taste Labs, Figment turns the rooms upside down, demonstrating how imagination can flip your perspective.
The ride culminates in the Imagination Lab, where Dr. Channing finally embraces the power of free-spirited imagination. The attraction concludes with an upbeat rendition of "One Little Spark," the iconic song written by the Sherman Brothers for the original Journey into Imagination.
The current version of the ride opened in 2002, following two previous iterations. The original Journey into Imagination (1983-1998) featured the Dreamfinder character alongside Figment and was widely beloved. Its replacement, Journey into YOUR Imagination (1999-2001), removed Figment and was poorly received, leading to the current version's creation.
The ride system uses a modified Omnimover-style vehicle called a "tour tram." Each tram can accommodate 7 riders (3 in the front row, 4 in the back). The attraction features a mix of physical sets, audio-animatronics, and screen-based effects to create its whimsical environments.
After exiting the ride, guests enter the ImageWorks area, an interactive play zone featuring various imagination-themed activities and games. This post-show area has evolved over the years but continues to be a popular part of the attraction experience.
Despite mixed reviews of the current iteration, Figment remains an iconic character for EPCOT. His enduring popularity is evident in the attraction's merchandise sales and the character's frequent appearance in EPCOT's festivals and marketing materials.
The attraction's longevity and Figment's status as an original EPCOT character contribute to its significance in Disney parks history. While many fans fondly remember the original version, Journey into Imagination with Figment continues to introduce new generations to the playful purple dragon and the power of imagination.

Name: Mission: SPACE
Location: World Discovery at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′26″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: August 15, 2003 (Mars Mission), August 13, 2017 (Earth Mission)
Height restriction: 40 inches (102 cm) for Green Mission, 44 inches (112 cm) for Orange Mission
Duration: 5:38 minutes
Thrill level: Thrill Ride, Spinning, Dark
Overview/History:
Mission: SPACE is a space exploration-themed pavilion and centrifugal motion simulator attraction that simulates astronaut training for the first crewed mission to Mars. The attraction offers two distinct experiences: the more intense Orange Mission to Mars and the less intense Green Mission orbiting Earth.
Upon entering the queue, guests find themselves in a futuristic space training center, complete with a replica of the planet Mars. The pre-show area features displays showcasing 75 years of human spaceflight and a rotating gravity wheel, setting the stage for the adventure ahead.
Riders board the X-2 Deep Space Shuttle, a fictional spacecraft said to use cutting-edge technologies like aerospike engines, solid hydrogen fuel, and carbon nanotubes. The Orange Mission includes a simulated liftoff from the International Space Training Center (ISTC), a slingshot around the moon, a period of hypersleep, and a landing on Mars. The Green Mission offers a gentler experience, taking guests on an orbiting tour of Earth before returning to the ISTC.
Each mission assigns riders one of four roles: navigator, pilot, commander, or engineer. During the flight, guests are called upon to perform critical tasks, adding to the immersive experience. The attraction uses a combination of a centrifuge mechanism, tilting capsules, and high-resolution computer-generated imagery to create a realistic sensation of space travel.
Mission: SPACE replaced the Horizons attraction, opening in 2003 at a cost of \$100 million. It was initially sponsored by Hewlett-Packard from 2003 to 2015. The attraction has undergone updates over the years, including the addition of the less intense Green Mission in 2017 to accommodate guests who may be prone to motion sickness.
The ride system consists of four separate centrifuges, each containing 10 capsules that can hold four riders each. The Orange Mission exposes riders to forces up to 2.5G, more than twice the force of gravity at Earth's surface. To enhance comfort and reduce motion sickness, gentle air circulation is provided within each capsule.
After the ride, guests can explore the Advanced Training Lab, an interactive play area featuring space-themed games and activities. The area includes Space Base, a playground for children, and Mission: SPACE Race, a collaborative game where up to 56 players can participate in a race to Mars.
Mission: SPACE pays homage to its predecessor, Horizons, with subtle references throughout the attraction. It also includes tributes to earlier Disney space-themed attractions like Mission to Mars from Magic Kingdom. The attraction's exterior, known as Planetary Plaza, features replicas of celestial bodies including the Moon, Earth, Jupiter, and Mars, with curved facades representing flight paths and orbits.

Name: Guardians of the Galaxy: Cosmic Rewind
Location: World Discovery at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′29″N 81°32′52″W
Opening date: May 27, 2022
Height restriction: 42 inches (107 cm)
Duration: 3:20 minutes
Thrill level: High-speed, Thrill Rides
Overview/History:
Guardians of the Galaxy: Cosmic Rewind is an enclosed roller coaster that takes guests on an intergalactic chase through space and time. As EPCOT's first roller coaster and Disney's first backwards-launched roller coaster, it offers a unique and thrilling experience for park visitors.
Upon entering the queue, guests find themselves in the Wonders of Xandar Pavilion, a clever nod to EPCOT's former Wonders of Life Pavilion. The queue showcases the outer world of Xandar, featured heavily in the Guardians of the Galaxy film franchise, through various exhibits and models, many with a humorous touch.
The adventure begins as guests are teleported aboard a Nova Corps ship for a demonstration of Xandar's cosmic generator. However, things quickly go awry when the generator is stolen, prompting the Guardians of the Galaxy to enlist the help of guests to chase down the thief and save the galaxy.
The ride itself is a thrilling experience that combines the excitement of a roller coaster with immersive storytelling. Featuring a unique ride system with vehicles that can rotate 360 degrees, Cosmic Rewind allows guests to focus on the action happening around them, which is displayed on massive screens throughout the attraction.
One of the most distinctive features of Cosmic Rewind is its music selection. Like the Guardians of the Galaxy films, music plays a crucial role in the attraction. The ride randomly selects one of six classic pop and rock songs for each journey, including "September" by Earth, Wind and Fire, and "Conga" by Miami Sound Machine, enhancing the experience and making each ride potentially different.
The attraction was announced as part of an overhaul of EPCOT at the 2017 D23 Expo. It replaced the Universe of Energy pavilion, which previously housed Ellen's Energy Adventure. The estimated cost of the attraction was \$500 million, showcasing Disney's significant investment in modernizing EPCOT.
Cosmic Rewind features a steel track that measures 5,577.4 feet (1,700 meters) in length. The ride can reach speeds of up to 60 mph (97 km/h) and occupies a massive 200,000 square foot (19,000 square meter) show building. Despite its thrilling nature, the ride doesn't include any inversions, making it accessible to a wider range of guests.
The attraction's cast includes several actors from the Guardians of the Galaxy films reprising their roles, including Chris Pratt as Peter Quill/Star-Lord, Zoe Saldaña as Gamora, and Dave Bautista as Drax. Glenn Close also returns as Nova Prime Irani Rael, while Terry Crews joins the cast as a new character, Centurion Tal Marik.
Since its opening, Guardians of the Galaxy: Cosmic Rewind has become one of EPCOT's most popular attractions, offering a perfect blend of thrilling ride experience and the beloved Guardians of the Galaxy humor and storytelling.

Name: Living with the Land
Location: World Nature at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′25.97″N 81°33′10.39″W
Opening date: October 1, 1982
Height restriction: None
Duration: 14:55 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
Living with the Land is a slow-moving boat ride that combines a dark ride with a tour through working greenhouses, showcasing innovative agricultural techniques and environmental stewardship. The attraction takes guests on a journey through the history of agriculture and into its future, demonstrating Disney's commitment to sustainable farming practices and cutting-edge horticultural science.
Your journey begins with a gentle boat ride through diverse ecosystems, including a tropical rainforest, a desert, and the American prairie. As you glide through these environments, you'll witness the interplay between the land and its inhabitants, setting the stage for the agricultural marvels to come.
The second half of the ride takes you through actual working greenhouses where Disney showcases various agricultural techniques. You'll see traditional crops alongside innovative growing methods like hydroponics, aeroponics, and aquaculture. Keep an eye out for uniquely shaped fruits and vegetables, including Mickey-shaped pumpkins and cucumbers.
Living with the Land was an opening day attraction for EPCOT, originally called "Listen to the Land." It was initially conceived as a hot-air balloon ride called "Blueprints of Nature," featuring a character known as the Landkeeper. However, when Kraft signed on as a sponsor, the concept changed to a boat ride, and the Landkeeper character was repurposed as the Dreamfinder for the Imagination pavilion.
The ride has undergone several updates since its opening. In 1993, it was renamed "Living with the Land," and the opening "Symphony of the Seed" sequence was replaced with the current thunderstorm scene. The attraction has been sponsored by Kraft (1982-1992), Nestlé (1993-2009), and Chiquita Brands International (2011-2020).
Each boat in Living with the Land can accommodate up to 40 guests in 10 rows. The ride system consists of 16 boats (with two spares) that continuously load and unload, allowing for a capacity of 1,600 riders per hour. The attraction features 35 audio-animatronics throughout the dark ride portion.
One of the unique aspects of Living with the Land is the "Behind the Seeds" tour, which allows guests to take a more in-depth look at the agricultural practices showcased in the ride. This one-hour walking tour provides a closer look at the fish farm and greenhouses, offering a hands-on experience with some of the gardening techniques demonstrated in the attraction.
Living with the Land remains a beloved attraction at EPCOT, maintaining the park's original vision of edutainment. It continues to inspire guests with its blend of entertainment and education, showcasing the importance of innovation in agriculture and environmental stewardship.

Name: The Seas with Nemo & Friends
Location: World Nature at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′25.97″N 81°33′10.39″W
Opening date: January 4, 2007 (as The Seas with Nemo & Friends)
Height restriction: None
Duration: Approximately 5 minutes (ride portion)
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
The Seas with Nemo & Friends is a family-friendly dark ride that takes guests on an underwater adventure through scenes inspired by the Disney-Pixar film "Finding Nemo." Located in the World Nature section of EPCOT, this attraction combines a slow-moving ride with one of the world's largest aquariums, creating a unique blend of fantasy and reality.
Your journey begins in a beach-themed queue, gradually transitioning to an underwater atmosphere as you approach the loading area. Guests board "Clamobiles," specially designed ride vehicles that carry them through the attraction. The ride tells the story of another search for Nemo, who has once again gone missing.
As you travel through vibrant coral reefs and the deep ocean, you'll encounter beloved characters from the film, including Marlin, Dory, Mr. Ray, and Bruce the shark. The ride culminates in a breathtaking scene where animated characters appear to swim alongside real sea life in the massive aquarium, achieved through innovative projection technology.
The attraction is housed in what was originally known as The Living Seas pavilion, which opened on January 15, 1986. At the time, its 5.7-million-gallon aquarium was the largest in the world. The pavilion underwent a major renovation and re-theming, reopening as The Seas with Nemo & Friends on January 4, 2007.
The transformation from The Living Seas to The Seas with Nemo & Friends was part of Disney's efforts to incorporate more character-based attractions into EPCOT. The renovation maintained the pavilion's focus on marine life and ocean conservation while adding the popular Nemo characters to increase appeal to younger visitors.
In addition to the ride, the pavilion houses several other attractions. Turtle Talk with Crush, an interactive show featuring the laid-back sea turtle from "Finding Nemo," opened in 2004 and was one of the first steps in the pavilion's transformation. The massive aquarium, now known as the Caribbean Coral Reef Aquarium, remains a central feature, home to over 4,000 sea creatures including sharks, sea turtles, and manatees.
The ride system consists of a continuous chain of Clamobiles moving through the attraction. Each Clamobile can hold up to three guests and features a single bench seat. The ride's capacity is approximately 2,200 riders per hour.
The Seas with Nemo & Friends showcases Disney's commitment to "edutainment," combining entertainment with education about marine life and conservation. While the ride portion focuses more on storytelling and character interactions, the surrounding exhibits in the pavilion provide opportunities for guests to learn about real marine ecosystems and the importance of ocean conservation.

Name: Turtle Talk with Crush
Location: The Seas with Nemo & Friends, World Nature at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′25.97″N 81°33′10.39″W
Opening date: November 16, 2004
Height restriction: None
Duration: 10-16 minutes
Thrill level: Interactive Show
Overview/History:
Turtle Talk with Crush is an innovative, interactive attraction that brings the laid-back sea turtle from Disney-Pixar's "Finding Nemo" to life in real-time conversations with guests. Located in The Seas with Nemo & Friends pavilion at EPCOT, this show combines cutting-edge digital puppetry technology with improvisational comedy to create a unique experience for every audience.
As guests enter the theater, they find themselves looking through a "window" into the East Australian Current, where Crush swims up to chat. The show's host introduces Crush, and then the turtle engages in unscripted interactions with the audience, answering questions and cracking jokes in his signature surfer-dude style.
The technology behind Turtle Talk with Crush is a marvel of Disney Imagineering. The "Window to the Pacific" is actually a large rear-projection screen displaying an animated undersea environment. Crush is a computer-generated character controlled by a hidden puppeteer whose performance is digitized and rendered in real-time at 60 frames per second. This allows Crush's mouth movements to sync perfectly with the actor's words, creating a seamless illusion of a talking turtle.
The puppeteer can see the audience through hidden cameras, allowing Crush to interact specifically with individual guests, commenting on their appearance or behavior. This level of personalization makes each show unique and engaging for both children and adults.
Turtle Talk with Crush was one of the first additions that kicked off the transformation of The Living Seas pavilion into The Seas with Nemo & Friends. It opened on November 16, 2004, and quickly became a guest favorite. The attraction's success led to versions being installed at other Disney parks worldwide, including Disney California Adventure, Tokyo DisneySea, and a temporary installation at Hong Kong Disneyland.
In 2016, the show received an update to include characters from the sequel film "Finding Dory," further enhancing the experience. Now, guests might also encounter Destiny the whale shark, Bailey the beluga whale, or Hank the octopus during their visit with Crush.
The attraction not only entertains but also educates guests about marine life and ocean conservation, aligning with EPCOT's mission of edutainment. It's a prime example of how Disney uses its beloved characters and advanced technology to create memorable experiences that also impart valuable knowledge.
Turtle Talk with Crush continues to be a popular attraction at EPCOT, delighting guests with its blend of humor, technology, and interactive fun. It stands as a testament to Disney's commitment to innovation in theme park entertainment and their ability to bring animated characters to life in new and exciting ways.


Name: Gran Fiesta Tour Starring The Three Caballeros
Location: Mexico Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: April 6, 2007
Height restriction: None
Duration: Approximately 8 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
Gran Fiesta Tour Starring The Three Caballeros is a musical dark boat ride that takes guests on a whimsical journey through Mexico. The attraction is housed within the iconic pyramid-shaped Mexico Pavilion in EPCOT's World Showcase.
Your adventure begins as you board a small boat and float gently into the heart of Mexico. The ride's storyline revolves around Panchito Pistoles and José Carioca searching for their missing friend, Donald Duck, who has run off to explore Mexico. As you glide through various scenes, you'll witness the vibrant culture, landmarks, and traditions of Mexico.
The journey starts with colorful posters announcing a concert by The Three Caballeros. Soon, you enter a tunnel where Panchito and José introduce themselves and realize Donald is missing. The subsequent scenes show Donald touring Mexico's famous sites, while his friends search for him on a magic serape (a flying Mexican blanket).
Throughout the ride, guests float past festive scenes featuring animated figures, live-action footage, and a blend of screens and practical sets. You'll see mariachi bands, traditional dancers, and even a Donald Duck piñata. The finale brings you to Mexico City, where fireworks light up the sky, and The Three Caballeros finally reunite for their grand concert.
Gran Fiesta Tour replaced the original El Rio del Tiempo (The River of Time) attraction, which had been in place since EPCOT's opening in 1982. The refurbishment in 2007 added the Disney characters and a more cohesive storyline while maintaining the ride's focus on Mexican culture and traditions.
The attraction's boats and flume system were manufactured by Arrow Dynamics, the same company that worked on other classic Disney water rides like "It's a Small World" and "Pirates of the Caribbean." Each boat can accommodate up to 16 riders, arranged in 5 rows.
A significant update occurred on December 4, 2015, when audio-animatronic figures of The Three Caballeros were added to the final scene. These animatronics were originally part of the Mickey Mouse Revue attraction from Magic Kingdom, adding a touch of Disney history to the ride.
The ride's animation was directed by Eric Goldberg, renowned for his work on Disney classics such as "Aladdin" (where he animated the Genie). This expertise brings a lively, authentic feel to the animated segments of the attraction.
Gran Fiesta Tour Starring The Three Caballeros continues to be a beloved attraction at EPCOT, offering a perfect blend of Disney charm and cultural exploration. It stands as the first World Showcase attraction to prominently feature Disney characters, paving the way for future character integrations in other pavilions.

Name: Frozen Ever After
Location: Norway Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: June 21, 2016
Height restriction: Any height
Duration: Approximately 5 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Small Drops, Dark
Overview/History:
Frozen Ever After is a musical dark ride that takes guests on a wondrous journey through the magical world of Arendelle from Disney's hit animated film "Frozen." The attraction replaced the former Maelstrom ride in the Norway Pavilion of EPCOT's World Showcase.
Your adventure begins as you board an ancient Norwegian vessel and set sail for a special "Summer Snow Day" celebration. The journey starts at the docks of Arendelle, where Olaf and Sven greet guests with a rendition of "Do You Want to Build a Snowman?" As you float through a frozen willow forest, you'll encounter Kristoff's family of trolls, who recount the story of how Anna saved Elsa.
Next, your boat ascends towards Elsa's ice palace atop the North Mountain. Here, you'll find Olaf ice skating and singing "For the First Time in Forever," followed by Anna and Kristoff joining in song. The highlight of the ride is witnessing Queen Elsa using her magical powers to conjure ice and snow while singing her signature song, "Let It Go."
The ride then takes an exciting turn as your boat reverses direction, passing through mist created by Marshmallow and the Snowgies from "Frozen Fever." After a short drop and on-ride photo opportunity, you'll sail past Arendelle Castle with fireworks bursting overhead. The journey concludes with Anna, Elsa, and Olaf bidding farewell as you return to the village.
Frozen Ever After utilizes the same ride system and track layout as its predecessor, Maelstrom, but with significant technological upgrades. The attraction features state-of-the-art Audio-Animatronics figures with digital projection technology for facial animations, creating more expressive and lifelike characters.
The ride's development was part of Disney's larger strategy to incorporate more character-based attractions into EPCOT, particularly in World Showcase. This decision was met with mixed reactions from Disney fans, with some praising the addition of popular characters and others expressing concern about maintaining the pavilion's cultural focus.
Since its opening, Frozen Ever After has become one of EPCOT's most popular attractions, often commanding long wait times. The ride's success has led to similar Frozen-themed attractions being developed for other Disney parks worldwide, including Hong Kong Disneyland and Tokyo DisneySea.
Frozen Ever After represents a blend of Disney's classic dark ride tradition with modern storytelling and technology, offering guests an immersive experience into the world of "Frozen" while maintaining a connection to Norwegian culture and mythology.

Name: Reflections of China
Location: China Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: May 22, 2003
Height restriction: None
Duration: 12 minutes and 30 seconds
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Standing
Overview/History:
Reflections of China is a Circle-Vision 360° movie that takes guests on a breathtaking tour of one of the world's oldest civilizations. The attraction is housed in a replica of the Temple of Heaven, an iconic structure from Beijing.
As you enter the theater, you'll find yourself standing in a circular room surrounded by nine screens. The show is narrated by Tang Dynasty poet Li Bai, who serves as your guide through China's rich history and diverse landscapes. The film showcases both ancient wonders and modern marvels, offering a comprehensive view of this vast country.
Your journey begins in Beijing, where you'll see the Forbidden City and Tiananmen Square. From there, you'll travel to iconic locations such as the Great Wall of China, the Yangtze River, and the karst mountains of Guilin. The film also highlights China's rapid modernization, featuring scenes of Shanghai's futuristic skyline and the bustling streets of Hong Kong.
Throughout the presentation, you'll witness traditional Chinese arts and customs, from tai chi practiced in parks to the famous terracotta warriors of Xi'an. The film captures the essence of China's natural beauty, showcasing pandas in their native habitat and the stunning landscapes of Huangshan (Yellow Mountain).
Reflections of China replaced its predecessor, Wonders of China, which had been showing since EPCOT's opening in 1982. While the basic concept remained the same, Reflections of China featured updated footage and a revised narrative to reflect China's changes over the two decades since the original film.
The Circle-Vision 360° technology used in Reflections of China creates a truly immersive experience. Nine cameras are used to capture the footage, which is then projected onto nine screens that completely surround the audience. This gives viewers the sensation of being in the middle of each scene, offering a unique perspective that traditional film cannot provide.
The musical score, composed by Bruce Broughton, blends traditional Chinese instruments with a full orchestra, enhancing the visual experience and evoking the spirit of each location shown.
Reflections of China represents Disney's ongoing commitment to showcasing world cultures in EPCOT's World Showcase. While providing entertainment, it also serves an educational purpose, offering many guests their first glimpse of China's diverse landscapes and rich cultural heritage.
As of 2024, plans are in place to replace Reflections of China with a new film titled "Wondrous China," which will utilize updated technology to provide an even more immersive experience. However, the opening date for this new attraction has been delayed due to various factors, including the global COVID-19 pandemic.

Name: The American Adventure
Location: World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′03″N 81°32′58″W
Opening date: October 1, 1982
Height restriction: None
Duration: 28:30 minutes
Thrill level: Theater Show
Overview/History:
The American Adventure is an impressive Audio-Animatronics stage show that takes guests on a journey through American history. Located in the American Adventure Pavilion between the Italy and Japan pavilions in EPCOT's World Showcase, this attraction offers a patriotic and educational experience.
As you enter the pavilion, you're greeted by a grand, 108-foot-tall building inspired by Georgian architecture, reminiscent of Colonial Williamsburg, Independence Hall, and Boston's Old State House. The interior features a 45-foot high rotunda adorned with patriotic quotes and artwork created by Disney Imagineers.
The show itself is presented in a theater-like auditorium with a capacity of 1,024 guests per show. It's narrated by Audio-Animatronic figures of Benjamin Franklin and Mark Twain, who serve as hosts and provide insightful commentary on American life throughout different historical periods.
The presentation uses a combination of film, audio-animatronics, and massive moving sets to bring American history to life. Scenes depict pivotal moments such as the landing of the Mayflower, the signing of the Declaration of Independence, the Civil War, and the Great Depression. The show concludes with a stirring musical film montage called "Golden Dream," showcasing famous moments and people in American history from post-World War II to the present day.
The American Adventure represents a significant technological achievement in Disney Imagineering. The show features 35 Audio-Animatronic figures and uses a complex system of lifts and hydraulics to raise and lower 12 massive sets weighing up to 175,000 pounds each. The rear-projection screen is a massive 72 feet wide and 28 feet tall, providing an immersive backdrop for the historical scenes.
Since its opening, the attraction has undergone several updates to keep it relevant. In 1993, all Audio-Animatronics were updated, and a new version of the theme song was introduced. The "Golden Dream" montage has been updated multiple times, most notably in 2007 to include footage of the September 11, 2001 rescue efforts, and again in 2018 to feature more recent historical figures and events.
The American Adventure exemplifies Disney's commitment to edutainment, offering a blend of historical accuracy, technological innovation, and emotional storytelling. It stands as a testament to the ideals and spirit of America, inviting guests to reflect on the nation's past and contemplate its future.

Name: Impressions de France
Location: France Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: October 1, 1982
Height restriction: None
Duration: 18:00 minutes
Thrill level: Theater Show
Overview/History:
Impressions de France is a breathtaking cinematic journey through the beauty and culture of France. Located in the Palais du Cinéma within EPCOT's France Pavilion, this attraction offers guests a stunning visual tour of the country's most iconic landmarks and landscapes.
As you enter the theater, you're greeted by the elegant ambiance of a French cinema. The film is projected onto five adjacent screens that provide a 200° field of view, creating an immersive experience that surrounds the audience. This unique format, while not as encompassing as the 360° films in other World Showcase pavilions, allows for a more cinematic presentation with carefully composed shots.
Your journey begins in the French countryside, where you'll see charming villages and rolling vineyards. The film then takes you on a grand tour of France's most famous sites, including the Palace of Versailles with its magnificent gardens, the iconic Eiffel Tower, the romantic streets of Paris, and the majestic French Alps. You'll witness the bustling activity of fishermen in Normandy, the elegance of the French Riviera, and the medieval splendor of Mont Saint-Michel.
Throughout the presentation, you're treated to a sweeping musical score arranged by Buddy Baker, featuring classical works by French composers such as Claude Debussy, Maurice Ravel, and Camille Saint-Saëns. The music perfectly complements the visuals, enhancing the emotional impact of each scene.
Impressions de France was directed by Rick Harper and written by Bob Rogers, a two-time Academy Award nominee. The film showcases 49 different locations throughout France, capturing the essence of French culture, history, and natural beauty. It's narrated in French by Claude Gobet, with English subtitles provided.
Since its opening in 1982, Impressions de France has remained largely unchanged, a testament to its timeless quality and enduring appeal. It holds the Guinness World Record for the "longest-running daily screening of a film in the same theater." The film's ability to transport viewers to France has made it a favorite among EPCOT guests for decades.
In recent years, Disney has adjusted the show schedule to accommodate the newer Beauty and the Beast Sing-Along attraction, which shares the same theater space. However, due to popular demand, Impressions de France continues to be shown in the evenings, allowing fans to experience this classic EPCOT attraction.
Impressions de France represents the pinnacle of Disney's commitment to cultural representation and cinematic artistry in EPCOT's World Showcase. It continues to inspire guests with its beautiful portrayal of France, encouraging many to plan their own visits to the country.

Name: Remy's Ratatouille Adventure
Location: France Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: October 1, 2021
Height restriction: None
Duration: 4:40 minutes
Thrill level: Slow Rides, Dark
Overview/History:
Remy's Ratatouille Adventure is a motion-based trackless 3D dark ride based on the 2007 Disney-Pixar animated film Ratatouille. The attraction takes guests on a whimsical culinary adventure through Gusteau's restaurant in Paris, where they are "shrunk" to the size of a rat.
Your journey begins on the rooftops of Paris, where you board rat-shaped vehicles called "ratmobiles." Guided by Chef Remy, you embark on a daring escapade through the bustling kitchen, dining room, and walls of Gusteau's famous restaurant. The ride uses cutting-edge trackless technology, allowing vehicles to move freely and unpredictably, enhancing the sense of adventure.
As you scurry through the kitchen, you'll encounter larger-than-life food props, 3D projections, and physical sets that create an immersive environment. The attraction employs various special effects, including scents that correspond to different areas of the restaurant, adding another layer of realism to the experience.
The ride features several key scenes, including a chase sequence through the walk-in freezer and under a hot oven, a chaotic moment in the dining area where guests attract attention from customers, and a final escape through the restaurant's walls. Throughout the adventure, you'll encounter characters from the film, including Chef Skinner and Alfredo Linguini.
Remy's Ratatouille Adventure was first conceptualized for Disneyland Paris, where it opened in 2014. The EPCOT version is nearly identical to its Parisian counterpart, with minor adjustments to fit the Florida park. The attraction's addition to EPCOT was part of a larger expansion of the France pavilion, which nearly doubled in size to accommodate the new ride and surrounding themed area.
The ride system consists of 36 vehicles, each capable of holding 6 riders in 2 rows of 3. The trackless system allows for a capacity of about 2,220 riders per hour. The attraction uses a combination of physical sets and 3D projection domes to create a seamless, immersive experience.
Imagineers paid close attention to details throughout the attraction and its surrounding area. The exterior queue features a grand fountain topped with a statue of Remy, and the pavement is adorned with rat footprints leading to the ride. Hidden details and Easter eggs, such as a silhouette of the Pizza Planet truck from Toy Story, can be found throughout the attraction.
Remy's Ratatouille Adventure represents Disney's commitment to bringing beloved animated properties to life in its theme parks. The attraction combines state-of-the-art ride technology with classic Disney storytelling to create a family-friendly experience that appeals to guests of all ages.

Name: Canada Far and Wide in Circle-Vision 360
Location: Canada Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: January 17, 2020
Height restriction: None
Duration: 14 minutes
Thrill level: Theater Show
Overview/History:
Canada Far and Wide in Circle-Vision 360 is an immersive travelogue that takes guests on a breathtaking journey across Canada's diverse landscapes and vibrant cities. The attraction is housed in the Canada Pavilion at EPCOT's World Showcase, offering visitors a stunning 360-degree view of the Great White North.
Your journey begins as you enter a theater designed to resemble the Rocky Mountains of British Columbia. As the show starts, you'll find yourself surrounded by sweeping vistas of Canada's natural wonders and urban centers. The film showcases the country's beauty from coast to coast, featuring iconic locations such as the majestic Canadian Rockies, the bustling streets of Toronto, the historic charm of Quebec City, and the rugged coastlines of the Atlantic provinces.
Throughout the presentation, you'll be treated to a newly composed musical score by Canadian composer Andrew Lockington, enhancing the emotional impact of each scene. The narration, provided by award-winning Canadian actors Catherine O'Hara and Eugene Levy, offers insightful commentary on the country's history, culture, and modern achievements.
Canada Far and Wide is the third iteration of the Circle-Vision 360 film in the Canada Pavilion since EPCOT's opening in 1982. The original film, "O Canada!", ran from 1982 to 2007. It was then updated and narrated by Canadian actor Martin Short, running from 2007 to 2019. The current version, which debuted in 2020, features a mix of new footage and digitally enhanced scenes from previous versions, offering a more contemporary and comprehensive view of Canada.
The film utilizes Circle-Vision 360° technology, which involves nine cameras arranged in a circular pattern to capture footage that completely surrounds the audience. The theater features nine screens arranged in a circle, with guests standing in the center, allowing for a truly immersive experience. This innovative presentation style gives viewers the sensation of being in the middle of each breathtaking scene.
Canada Far and Wide not only showcases the country's natural beauty but also highlights its cultural diversity. The film includes segments featuring Indigenous peoples and their traditions, as well as showcasing Canada's multicultural urban centers. It also touches on Canada's contributions to science, technology, and the arts.
This attraction represents Disney's ongoing commitment to providing educational and entertaining experiences in EPCOT's World Showcase. By combining stunning visuals, informative narration, and a touch of humor, Canada Far and Wide offers guests a comprehensive and engaging overview of Canada, inspiring many to explore the country further.

Name: Luminous: The Symphony of Us
Location: World Showcase Lagoon at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: December 5, 2023
Height restriction: None
Duration: 17 minutes
Thrill level: Nighttime Spectacular
Overview/History:
Luminous: The Symphony of Us is a fireworks-based nighttime spectacular that celebrates the passage of life, cultures, and customs shared across global communities. The show debuted on December 5, 2023, coinciding with Walt Disney's 122nd birthday and as part of the centennial anniversary of The Walt Disney Company.
Your experience begins as voices from around World Showcase welcome you to "the great gathering." The show unfolds through a series of movements, each representing different stages of life and human connection. Synchronized pyrotechnics, choreographed water fountains, lasers, searchlights, and fire torches create a 360° audio-visual experience on the World Showcase Lagoon.
Throughout the performance, you'll hear a mix of new arrangements of beloved Disney songs and two original compositions. The show begins with "Heartbeat Symphony," an original song that sets the tone for the journey. As the spectacle progresses, you'll recognize familiar tunes like "You'll Be in My Heart" from Tarzan, "Proud Corazón" from Coco, and "Into the Unknown" from Frozen II, among others. The finale features another original song, "Beating of Our Hearts," bringing the show to a powerful conclusion.
Luminous: The Symphony of Us was developed by Disney Live Entertainment under the direction of Steve Davison, vice president of parades and spectaculars. The show's music, a crucial element of the experience, was composed by Pinar Toprak, known for her work on Captain Marvel and the "EPCOT Anthem." The score was recorded across multiple locations, including Glasgow with the Royal Scottish National Orchestra, London with London Voices, as well as in New York, Nashville, and Orlando.
The show utilizes seven large barges and dozens of smaller platforms equipped with fountains, lights, and fireworks launchers. This setup, along with additional fireworks launched from around the lagoon perimeter, allows for a more immersive and visually stunning experience compared to its predecessors. The removal of the large, permanent structures used in the previous show, Harmonious, has significantly improved viewing angles from around World Showcase Lagoon.
Luminous: The Symphony of Us represents Disney's ongoing commitment to creating emotional and technologically advanced nighttime spectaculars. It aims to strike a balance between the high-concept approach of IllumiNations: Reflections of Earth and the Disney-centric focus of Harmonious, offering a show that is both entertaining and thematically resonant with EPCOT's mission of global unity and human connection.

Name: The British Revolution
Location: United Kingdom Pavilion, World Showcase at EPCOT
Coordinates: 28°22′19″N 81°32′48″W
Opening date: October 1, 2001
Height restriction: None
Duration: Approximately 20-30 minutes per set
Thrill level: Live Music Performance
Overview/History:
The British Revolution is a lively musical performance that takes place at the United Kingdom Pavilion in EPCOT's World Showcase. This band celebrates the rich musical heritage of Britain by performing classic rock hits from the 1960s and 1970s, captivating audiences with their energetic renditions and authentic sound.
The performance area is situated near the Rose & Crown Pub, where guests can enjoy a pint while listening to the band. The intimate setting allows for close interaction between the performers and the audience, enhancing the overall experience.
The British Revolution's setlist features iconic songs from legendary British bands, including The Beatles, The Rolling Stones, The Who, and Led Zeppelin. Their performances not only entertain but also showcase the cultural significance of British rock music and its influence worldwide.
One of the highlights of The British Revolution is the opportunity for guest interaction. After performances, band members often engage with the audience, taking photos and chatting with fans, which adds a personal touch to the experience.
The band has continued to perform regularly at EPCOT, adapting their setlist and style to keep the performances fresh and engaging. They are known for their vibrant energy and ability to connect with audiences of all ages, making them a beloved part of the EPCOT entertainment lineup.
The British Revolution exemplifies EPCOT's commitment to cultural representation and live entertainment, allowing guests to immerse themselves in the sounds of British rock while enjoying the picturesque surroundings of the United Kingdom Pavilion. Their ongoing performances contribute to the vibrant atmosphere of World Showcase, making it a must-see for visitors to EPCOT.

